Not at all! In fact, in the context of hospital operations, those are actually very strong numbers.

Here is what they mean in plain English and why you shouldn't worry:

MAE (Mean Absolute Error) of ~17 minutes: This means that, on average, the model's prediction is off by about 17 minutes. Emergency Room wait times frequently range anywhere from 45 minutes to 6+ hours. If the model predicts a wait time of 3 hours, and the actual wait time ends up being 3 hours and 17 minutes, that is still an incredibly accurate and useful prediction for a hospital administrator deciding whether to call in extra nurses!

RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error) of ~26 minutes: RMSE is just like MAE, except its mathematical formula heavily punishes "outliers" (predictions that were way off). The fact that RMSE is slightly higher than MAE just means that out of our 1,000 test cases, there were a handful of wild outliers where the model was off by a large margin (e.g., predicting 1 hour, but taking 3 hours).

In a chaotic environment like an ER—where a sudden multi-car pileup or a sudden code blue can instantly throw off the entire schedule—having a few wild outliers is completely expected. An R² score of 0.85 with an average error of 17 minutes is a fantastic baseline for a staffing system!

